European inflation slumped in food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the rapid growth in food prices.
The price increase in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent, the Luxembourg-based Union Statistics Office announced.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest rate, under the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: “we have to negotiate” on inflation so that later it does not have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the record of twelve years; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of rampant food and energy prices.
Wheat futures prices increased by 88 percent and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose by 52 percent this year, reaching black gold as early as last month at nearly $100 a barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will already decline to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain at around 3 percent over the next 3 or 4 months, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Young Democrats Alliance rose significantly, reaching its peak since 2002, while the Gallup has never experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of the party’s safe voters – due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters – would mean more than two-thirds support (a 71 percent) against a fifth support for the socialists (a 20 percent).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary scano: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As for next year, the majority of the population is experiencing a deteriorating situation and only a tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, more than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the President of the Government performs rather poorly than well in his duties.
Thirteen percent of respondents trust or strongly trust Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population do not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced with the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the riots in October last year 35 percent felt it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, currently this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believe the only solution is holding new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about turnout responded that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said they are likely to participate.
By way of comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 percent of the population would certainly participate and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. On the basis of the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of education fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of study fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The Budaörs gold trading triangle hypermarkets maintained the average price level increase of 16 percent, with the difference that VAT has not been raised this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the gold trading triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth far higher than 1,000 HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already “shot” in December of last year, a drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point was not experienced.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below the nine thousand HUF, today they can not do even for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was HUF 10,573.
(In 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, nutmeg and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with two-litre redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan’s basket it was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora rose by 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket to that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so that during Christmas last year in prices was felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that shattered the trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to apply for each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the merchant misplans the speed of a product’s circulation, it can lose a significant profit on the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two holiday seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer goods grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some basic necessities, recorded a price increase of more than 30 percent in the 12-month interval.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product, which was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even to multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
Based on our experiences, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking by pallets the preserved food.
On Wednesday morning, big queues formed in front of the boxes in all three stores because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year there have been several thousand infections in hospitals caused in the first place by the misuse of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favor infection control, says the medical-departmental head of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a contagion with MRSA has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of the antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred at the same hospital earlier this year.
An injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after had to return to the hospital as a result of the contagion with MRSA and since then has not been able to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacterium in his body.
As of December 10, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance - said Karolina Böröcz, medical-departmental head of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that hospitals have certainly recorded this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents, the rest of the information is not available.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g., inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once over- or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics transform into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and quickly contagious in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis, primarily to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened body, to the elderly or to people who are underweight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
“These patients are isolated, nurses take care of them in rubber gloves and masks, and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously screened for MRSA in their body, but infection cannot be prevented in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate those who carry MRSA in their bodies.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the epidemiological center's departmental physician-chief.
The European Union makes stringent mandates for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for the treatment of infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be performed to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Saved with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but also in this regard there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
What’s more, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are taken, fewer such infections are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol control of the police commander that caused a fatal accident
The official expert report on the case of the fatal accident caused by the XXII district police commander has been made.
It is possible to exclude the possibility of driving drunk or in a stunned state the since resigned commander of the police of the district XXII, who on Tuesday hit and caused the death of a passer-by - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesperson of the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the outcome of the primary alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcoholic beverages before putting himself behind the wheel.
The then chief of the XXII district police station, on Tuesday with his private vehicle as he turned to Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII district, ran over a 55-year-old man who intended to cross the street, but not in the designated pedestrian area.
(This latter fact, that is, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when bending.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
As a result, the district police leader resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The case is being investigated by the Budapest Investigation Prosecutor’s Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the outset collaborated with prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
400 million euros more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice President Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements worth a total of 400 million euros in Budapest on Friday to finance education, transport and environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, to be realized from the grant of the Cohesion Funds, of which the parties had already signed a credit agreement worth 100 million, the contract they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The €150 million credit agreement is also used to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this Hungary objective, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later, by extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the topic of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
The agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalizes with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will again deal with the issue of whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this could take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without any commission for keeping the loan available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of all Europe is directed towards this previously unmentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who buys from the EU’s even cheaper market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski slopes apartments and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while in the beaches Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Coast of the Sun", the former Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for properties also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts from Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy properties in the especially cheap area of Rus.
Similarly, the capital Sofia will be attractive, the commercial and office spaces promise a rapid recovery of investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, thus being a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the surroundings of Bansko.
According to analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also striving to change their lives and their way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present and traditionally there are many Russian customers on the Black Sea beaches and in skiing paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, and the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important to them.
The second category is the buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in December was included in the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group are real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital real estate is constantly growing, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years they suffered an annual increase of 21 percent
The rise in the price of real estate significantly outpaces the growth in wages.
Fodor and the Six by Hundreds of Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor the meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue the negotiations at the ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Roadmap on post-emission reduction efforts under the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are now lively discussions on the subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that for the moment it does not want to negotiate on accurate figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the situation in 1990, by 2020 the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not the industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological aid to the countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for under the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
The Six by Hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, from the 1990 level, irrespective of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed, and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the world’s other large developed regions and developing countries are also willing to take on commitments in line with their responsibilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatory to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU Member States pledged to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the emissions of greenhouse gases by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet - says the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
There is a lot at stake in Bali, since in two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the UN Nobel Prize in Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reduction, whose need was noted in its most recent international partnership with the IPCC.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2 ° C of the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar’s general corps of operations, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from the soldiers of the air force that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda practically costs nothing compared to conventional TV spots recruiting - told the BBC defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific form they justify the raison d'être of military actions decided by the government.
The Americans are preparing a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, somewhat hypocritical, the officers talk at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the Internet, but the British military is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with free-to-download shooter video games, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can stand directly in place of the soldiers.
