The reception will be held at Vajdahunyad Castle in the Municipal Park and according to the portfolio, there will be a budget of 1000 HUF per person for the one hundred guests.
This - according to the press department - will be a very simple standing reception, to which only specialized diplomats, accredited in Hungary, will be invited.
These receptions, which are held every year, begin with a brief greeting speech from the minister and conclude with a modest meal.
The Ministries of Foreign Affairs and of Education and Culture will not celebrate any Christmas - this is what the corresponding press departments informed [origo].
In the press department of the environment portfolio they were unable to report on the budget of the Ministry's Christmas celebrations.
What is known is that for the party to be held at the Museum of Applied Arts more than four hundred people were invited.
The Forces of the Giant Strike are Gathering
The League Trade Unions and the National Federation of Workers’ Commissions will set up a strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday’s strike that will last indefinitely.
On Saturday, a protest rally will be held, while on Monday – the day on which the final vote on the public health law will be held – work stoppage will begin.
Certainly this action will cause great difficulties in transport, since the rail transit will be stopped completely and until 1 p.m. the workers of the Budapest Collective Transport Company will also be on strike.
In the afternoon of Friday, the League Unions will inform about the details of their strike on Monday, which they will hold together with the National Federation of Workers’ Commissions.
The strike committee of the LIGA and the National Machinist Union will also be set up to coordinate Monday’s actions.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while participating unions will strike indefinitely on Monday, if no agreement is reached with the government.
This means that - on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law - they did not report on the date of the end of the strike that began.
If the National Assembly disapproves of the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their call for strikes.
Instead, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
On the basis of the National Assembly’s Monday agenda, it is also possible that the public health law may only be voted on in the early evening hours, or perhaps close to midnight.
As a result of the strike that will begin on Monday, significant difficulties in transport will have to face: in the railways will stop working indefinitely, in the morning may stop part of the collective transport of Budapest and more than half of the intercity bus transport of the Volán companies.
At the same time, in many parts of the country, half of the roads will be closed.
Numerous trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, and their names are constantly updated on the League's website.
Some unions announced their strike indefinitely, others for a defined time.
Until Thursday afternoon the State Railway and the Free Railway Workers Union (SLTF) could not reach an agreement even on minimum services, although, as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are traveling on trains.
According to information received so far, from the beginning of the day until 1 p.m., the workers of the Budapest Collective Transport Company, the Budapest Airports from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m., will be on strike for four hours, the LIGA Trade Unions of the Electrical and Thermal Energy Industry, the Trade Unions of the Educators called for a strike of 2 hours.
The Hungarian Association of Physicians will strike nationally at alternative times and the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers (SDTSSS), which is part of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum, will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal on public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is that they gradually introduce the new form of pension calculation that will come into effect next year.
The third is that they ensure, even before 2010, for advanced pensions the possibility that the occupations that merit it can enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF), which is part of the League Trade Unions, do not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway sidelines and expect another different proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: In the country the risk is increased by the Hungarian Guard
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was formed in August of this year with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region from several points of view.
The company’s “risk warning” states: in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is the fact that “with the escalation of ethnic tensions between the gypsy and non-gypsy populations of Hungary, even in the short term violent ethnic clashes can occur”.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably the provocation of an event of this nature - added the representative of the research institute.
They said that all this is due to one of the main faults of the protagonists of Hungarian political life: "the protagonists of public life gave the public debate of the gypsy problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on the existing discrepancies between gypsy and hungarians."
This aggravates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of the outbreak of violent conflicts - they estimate.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially in relation to the stability and democratic development of the country."
They remind us that since the autumn of 2006, the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has received increasing publicity and momentum, and that since the summer of 2007 numerous organizations have been formed in the country that define themselves as "national self-defense associations".
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the training of their members for defense - even armed - (civil defense, national defense, defense of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, i.e. the state," they add.
They said: all this is done in accordance with the method that tries to give a civilian presentation to different political aspirations, based on society’s dissatisfaction with politics and with political parties.
