The Serbs and Albanians of Kosovo ended Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, a sixth and final session of discussions without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is unfortunate that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status," European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was " at stake " , his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their efforts to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
" We do not foresee violence for now but we are entering a very difficult period " , he added, noting that " obvious tensions exist " .
End of mediation on December 10
The mediators of the troika, which regroups the European Union, the United States and Russia, will go one last time Monday to Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the 90 percent Albanian-populated province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko return their relationship to the United Nations Security Council by Dec. 10.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final session of negotiations since the troika was tasked with a new mediation by the UN last August.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation to end on Dec. 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence in Kosovo in the Security Council, insist on pursuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," Botsane-Khartchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, the Westerners consider independence under the supervision of the European Union to be the only viable solution.
Pristina feels ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not resolve in her favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden where these "last chance negotiations" were held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, has expressed some of his regrets.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that has led to homicides and deportations."
" Domino Effect "
Serbian President Boris Tadic, for his part, considered that a compromise was always feasible, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the independence of the province.
Belgrade particularly said it feared a " domino effect " in a region still weakened by the wars of independence in the 1990s.
For Serbia, he said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that all decisions belong exclusively to the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has a right of veto.
" The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word "
“Only one solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia,” Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
"These negotiations have lasted two years.
They must end up as they have started: in the Security Council.”
To journalists, Fatmir Sedjiu had replied that " the Kosovo Parliament will have the final say on the status " , adding that any unilateral declaration of independence on the part of the Albanians would be made " in consultation " with the Westerners.
