What insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver in the event of possible accidents, is an important expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, gender, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Having a car is just the beginning.
Choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the vehicle model.
First of all, we need to be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is materialized in an insurance contract, which provides that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of an accident.
The premium is the price of insurance, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use that is given to it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so that the more likely you are to suffer an accident, the higher the fee to be paid.
It is for this reason that both people over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics reflect that they have a lower accident rate due to their prudence.
In addition, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will influence the frequency, and thus the probability of having some kind of mishap.
As the frequency increases, the odds increase.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
That is why the driver has to study the situation well to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
We will present here the most significant variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers you a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 are faced with various drawbacks when it comes to taking out insurance at an affordable price, such as reduced driving experience and the age of the card.
Although the ideal for being well insured is full-risk insurance, there are other, more economical options.
The more cautious drivers can opt for a full-risk franchise, so they get full-risk insurance coverage but at a more feasible price.
This kind of agreement would require the customer to pay a portion of the claim amount.
"The part of the amount of the claim provided by the customer will be pre-set according to the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount," specifies Luis Noguera, Spain's chief executive of First Europe, an online insurance broker.
Another option is an extended third-party insurance, so that the customer ensures protection against damage caused to third parties, although not against those caused in his own car.
In addition, it would be covered by theft, fire and the loss of the vehicle.
A piece of advice.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus, and may reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate owned by the company.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on such a base fare.
“The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and the company’s benefit.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the bonuses,” explains Noguera.
After the age of 25, drivers have it easier to take out insurance, since the accident rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is most advisable to hire a full risk with franchise.
“Normally young people cannot make use of the experience previously gained when using an accident, and even when driving,” says the director in Spain of the European company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the ‘fear of the rookie’ has passed.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children, it is preferable that he negotiate full-risk insurance, as long as his economic situation allows it, of course.
For their part, marriages with children are considered by insurers as the public with the lowest accident rate, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be one at all risk with franchise (which may be 300 euros), or, when a high level of bonus is available, one extended to third parties from the third year of life of the vehicle.
"They conduct a more relaxed driving and have greater purchasing power to afford to assume a greater amount of franchise," says Luis Noguera.
For retirees it is advisable to have a full-risk insurance with franchise (this being 150 euros), or one extended to third parties when you have a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver in the face of possible accidents, but also because it represents a significant expense, which is why it is essential to study adequately the insurance that suits us according to our personal situation.
