Is the Subprime Mortgage Crisis Infecting the U.S. Credit Card Market?
When there is blood in the water, it is natural that some dorsal fins swim excitedly around.
Now that the American housing market is in crisis, predators have their eyes on the credit card market of the country.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of contagion are already seen.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been amortized or are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken over 1.4 million in its U.S. consumer financing business, in part due to weak card borrowers.
However, it is too early for panic.
Delinquency and delinquency are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a rating agency, the third quarter crime rate of 3.89% was almost a percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the U.S. Individual Bankruptcy Act (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore, delinquency) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also reports solid payout rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay each month.
And trust in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emission volumes for 2007 will be about 25 percent higher than last year.
The direct channels of infection of the crisis between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge credit cards with debts now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look at liquidity flow more than active securities, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ credit capacity.
They can even work to outperform issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue amortizing the mortgage decrease if the properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, the payment of the card’s debt rises on the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders face by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That should in theory reduce the risk of a rapid asset retaking.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and re-evaluate all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, head of finance at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If home prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a more severe future.
We need to keep an eye on those back fins.
