Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that so far had not been raised. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that rays could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays silence from a height of 54 kilometers of one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to Urey-Miller’s famous life-origin model, lightning caused life on Earth: Storms may have triggered reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the building blocks of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there was life there someday, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C prevail on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Perhaps, Venus is a 'devil' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many papers in Nature, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
“This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed,” ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers also discovered in the south polar region a vortex formed by clouds spinning faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called the dawn star or evening star orbiting the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not resemble Earth much, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had agglomerated which on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon rocks, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
